Tungsten — whole-stage code generation.

Catalyst gives you the right plan. Tungsten is what makes that plan run fast on the java virtual machine. Two ideas do most of the work.

The first is off-heap memory management. Spark allocates structured binary buffers off the java heap, which bypasses the garbage collector. That means less garbage-collector pause time, and memory layouts that are far friendlier to the cache-pee-you cache.

The second is whole-stage code generation. For each stage, Catalyst generates a single, tightly-fused java method that pushes a row through every operator at once — filter, then project, then aggregate — in one loop. Compare that with the alternative, which is one method call per operator, per row.

This is the deep reason dataframes beat R-D-Ds on structured data. An R-D-D has no schema, so Tungsten cannot lay it out efficiently or generate stage-level code. With a dataframe, the schema is a contract that Tungsten can compile against.

And you can see the proof directly in a physical plan. The dataframe operators are wrapped in a whole-stage-codegen block, where the number in that block is the codegen stage identifier.
